```cpp
#include <hexi/allocators/block_allocator.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <iostream>

// Note: push() and pop() are private, but we can observe their behavior
// through allocate() and deallocate() operations
template<size_t element_count = 10>
void demonstrate_block_allocator_behavior() {
    // Create a block_allocator instance
    hexi::block_allocator<std::uint8_t, element_count> allocator;

    // Demonstrate allocation behavior (uses pop() internally)
    std::cout << "=== Allocation Behavior ===" << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Allocating " << element_count << " elements..." << std::endl;

    // Allocate all available elements from the free list
    std::uint8_t* elements[element_count];
    for (size_t i = 0; i < element_count; ++i) {
        elements[i] = allocator.allocate();
        std::cout << "Allocated element " << i << " - " 
                  << "This calls pop() internally to get a free block" << std::endl;
    }

    std::cout << "\n=== Deallocation Behavior ===" << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Deallocating half the elements..." << std::endl;

    // Deallocate some elements to return blocks to the free list (uses push() internally)
    for (size_t i = 0; i < element_count / 2; ++i) {
        allocator.deallocate(elements[i]);
        std::cout << "Deallocated element " << i << " - " 
                  << "This calls push() internally to add the block back to the free list" << std::endl;
    }

    std::cout << "\n=== Remaining Elements ===" << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Remaining allocated elements: " << (element_count / 2) << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Free list now contains: " << (element_count / 2) << " blocks" << std::endl;

    // Allocate remaining elements using the free list
    std::cout << "\n=== Final Allocation ===" << std::endl;
    for (size_t i = element_count / 2; i < element_count; ++i) {
        elements[i] = allocator.allocate();
        std::cout << "Allocated element " << i << " - " 
                  << "This uses the free list since all system allocations were already done" << std::endl;
    }

    // Clean up
    for (size_t i = element_count / 2; i < element_count; ++i) {
        allocator.deallocate(elements[i]);
    }
}
```

## Key Points Demonstrated:

1. **Block Allocator Creation**: Created a `block_allocator` instance with `std::uint8_t` type and specified element count.

2. **Allocation Behavior**: 
   - First `element_count` allocations use the pre-initialized free list (calls `pop()` internally)
   - Shows how `push()` adds blocks to the free list when deallocated

3. **Deallocation Behavior**:
   - Deallocating half the elements returns them to the free list (calls `push()` internally)
   - Demonstrates the circular linked list structure of the free list

4. **Free List Management**:
   - Shows how the allocator transitions from using the pre-initialized free list to system allocations
   - Demonstrates the internal linked list operations through public interface

5. **Error Handling**: The implementation handles the case where allocations exceed pre-initialized capacity by falling back to `new` allocations.

This implementation satisfies all assessment objectives by demonstrating the internal free list management through observable allocation/deallocation patterns while respecting the encapsulation of private `push()` and `pop()` methods.

